<p>We built an Everybot last year, and basically ported and modified this code for our arm.</p>
<p>Depending on the dynamics of what you are trying to control (arm, elevator, lateral motion, telescoping, etc.) your feedforward methodology might change.</p>
<p>The arm on the Everybot last year was a kinematic NIGHTMARE to model in software (silicon bungee tubing, and an arm that folds into and out of itself, etc) . Our solution? We didn’t even bother with feedforward!</p>
<p>The saying goes that if you get your feedforward correct, you should barely need to do ANY pid control on position. Ironically, we found that even without ANY feedforward, we were able to get pretty smooth motion with only proportional <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> control on a dynamically insane arm. For what it’s worth, we also did not even use an absolute encoder - we used the NEO built-in encoder (ie. prior to reduction).</p>
